		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Measuring the relevance and alignment of your Twitter audience (featuring @ladygaga, @darthvader and more!)]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk/2011/04/19/measuring-the-relevance-and-alignment-of-your-twitter-audience/" />
		<id>http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk/?p=3056</id>
		<updated>2011-04-19T08:51:47Z</updated>
		<published>2011-04-19T07:56:23Z</published>
		<category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="Visualization" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="measurement" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="twitter" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="alignment" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="data" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="relevance" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="tool" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="venn" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="venn diagram" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="visualisation" />		<summary type="html"><![CDATA[In which I present a simple methodology for measuring (and visualising!) the relevance and alignment of your Twitter audience with the power of Venn diagrams!]]></summary>
		<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk/2011/04/19/measuring-the-relevance-and-alignment-of-your-twitter-audience/"><![CDATA[<p>We all know, it’s not just the <em>number</em> of followers on Twitter you have, but the <em>quality</em> of those followers, that matters. It’s much more meaningful to be followed by <a href="http://twitter.com/BarackObama">Barack Obama</a> than your <a href="http://twitter.com/YourAuntBarbara">Auntie Barbara</a>, for instance.</p>
<p>But, how can we measure the quality of our audience effectively? One factor of quality that can be measured is the alignment between your followers’ interests and your own. By measuring this, we can see if we’re reaching the people we want to reach.</p>
<p>I’d like to introduce a simple but quite effective approach I’ve been playing with recently, which uses that marvelous, much-loved invention of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Venn">John Venn</a>, the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venn_diagrams">Venn diagram</a>, to try and establish a method of measuring alignment and relevance.</p>
<p>By first harvesting sets of followers of select Twitter accounts (through Twitter’s <a href="http://dev.twitter.com/doc/">API</a>), and then overlaying those sets in Venn diagram fashion, we’re able to gain a quick, visible gauge of how closely aligned, or opposed, those Twitter accounts are. This gives us an instantly-understandable snapshot of how appealing one particular person, or brand, on Twitter is to the followers of another Twitter account, and helps us understand the size, quality and interests of our audience.</p>
<p><strong>A quick example to illustrate the idea&#8230;</strong></p>
<p><a title="Followers of @ladygaga, @katyperry and @RIHANNA by NixonMcInnes, on Flickr" rel="shadowbox[tweetspot];content=http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5229/5631917631_9800fee578_o.png" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nixonmcinnes/5631917631/"><img src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5229/5631917631_01a87bfb5e.jpg" alt="Followers of @ladygaga, @katyperry and @RIHANNA" width="430" height="323" /></a></p>
<p>This diagram represents the <strong>13.5 million</strong> people who follow either <a href="http://twitter.com/ladygaga">Lady Gaga</a> or <a href="http://twitter.com/katyperry">Katy Perry</a> or <a href="http://twitter.com/rihanna">Rihanna</a> on Twitter. We can see that Gaga has the largest fan base of all three, followed by Perry and then Rihanna, with <strong>1.8 million</strong> people following all three performers.</p>
<p>Looking more closely,  it’s interesting to note that while a sizable portion of Rihanna’s followers also follow either Perry or Gaga (<strong>68%</strong>), there is slightly more similarity, or <em>cohesion</em>, between Gaga/Perry fans than Perry/Rihanna fans (<strong>58%</strong> of Katy Perry’s followers also follow Lady Gaga, whereas <strong>35%</strong> of Perry fans follow Rihanna).  Maybe Katy Perry and Lady Gaga should perform a duet? Just imagine the pandemonium that would ensue! Well, I’m fairly certain <a href="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk/people/ross"><abbr title="Ross Breadmore">Ross</abbr></a> would rush out and buy the single, anyway.</p>
<p>So, here are some more variations on this theme (selected from <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nixonmcinnes/sets/72157626526691196/show/">this Flickr photoset</a>), some are perhaps rather contrived, and others just plain geeky/silly/fun, but there are some serious applications thrown in too for good measure, so look out! :)</p>
<p><strong>First of all, let&#8217;s see how the followers of @<a href="http://twitter.com/darthvader">darthvader</a>, @<a href="http://twitter.com/lordpalpatine">lordpalpatine</a> (Vader’s boss) and @<a href="http://twitter.com/wwwfoecouk">wwwfoecouk</a> (Friends of the Earth) compare&#8230;</strong></p>
<p><a title="Followers of @darthvader, @LordPalpatine and @wwwfoecouk by NixonMcInnes, on Flickr" rel="shadowbox[tweetspot];content=http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5269/5632501258_8b54fa3766_o.png" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nixonmcinnes/5632501258/"><img src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5269/5632501258_0a01077805.jpg" alt="Followers of @darthvader, @LordPalpatine and @wwwfoecouk" width="430" height="323" /></a></p>
<p>Here we see a mahoosive <strong>75%</strong> of Palpatine’s followers also follow Vader, indicating Vader’s evil antics appeal highly to fans of the Dark Side’s Emperor. Meanwhile, there’s not much love between this pair of evil fiends and Friends of the Earth, in fact the two are almost diametrically opposed. The fact that Vader and Palpatine aren’t best mates with the Earth, while disturbing, should not entirely surprise us. It’s just a good job Palpatine and Vader don’t actually exist, eh?</p>
<p><strong>Moving swiftly on&#8230;</strong></p>
<p><a title="Followers of @darthvader, @justinbieber and @ladygaga by NixonMcInnes, on Flickr" rel="shadowbox[tweetspot];content=http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5303/5632501162_c8e454b339_o.png" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nixonmcinnes/5632501162/"><img src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5303/5632501162_79bf3ebea7.jpg" alt="Followers of @darthvader, @justinbieber and @ladygaga" width="430" height="323" /></a></p>
<p>In terms of audience size, there’s little between the young upstart <a href="http://twitter.com/justinbieber">Bieber</a> and Lady Gaga, but it seems Gaga has a dark side that is more appealing to the Vader contingent.</p>
<p><strong>Next up&#8230;</strong></p>
<p><a title="Followers of @50cent, @english50cent and @queenlizii by NixonMcInnes, on Flickr" rel="shadowbox[tweetspot];content=http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5021/5631917337_8b33a189e7_o.png" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nixonmcinnes/5631917337/"><img src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5021/5631917337_899a3d48d2.jpg" alt="Followers of @50cent, @english50cent and @queenlizii" width="430" height="323" /></a></p>
<p>Looks like the inimitable <a href="http://twitter.com/english50cent">English 50 Cent</a> is doing a fine job of translating <a href="http://twitter.com/50cent">Fiddy</a>’s tweets for followers of the <a href="http://twitter.com/queenlizii">Queen</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Let&#8217;s see how love rivals @<a href="http://twitter.com/misskatieprice">misskatieprice</a> (AKA jordan), @<a href="http://twitter.com/MrPeterAndre">MrPeterAndre</a> and @<a href="http://twitter.com/Only1AlexReid">Only1AlexReid</a> fare&#8230;</strong></p>
<p><a title="Followers of @misskatieprice, @MrPeterAndre and @Only1AlexReid by NixonMcInnes, on Flickr" rel="shadowbox[tweetspot];content=http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5186/5631917179_1d72a87a18_o.png" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nixonmcinnes/5631917179/"><img src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5186/5631917179_aaf596a8c8.jpg" alt="Followers of @misskatieprice, @MrPeterAndre and @Only1AlexReid" width="430" height="323" /></a></p>
<p>With <strong>77.4%</strong> of his followers also following Miss Price and Mr Andre, is Alex Reid a mere pawn in the ongoing, tabloid-fuelled rift between the once happily married couple?</p>
<p><strong>Moving quickly on to slightly more credible territory&#8230;</strong></p>
<p><a title="Followers of @arsenal, @persie_official and @FlyingEmirates by NixonMcInnes, on Flickr" rel="shadowbox[tweetspot];content=http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5070/5631917065_9c73bd194f_o.png" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nixonmcinnes/5631917065/"><img src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5070/5631917065_7c7106e875.jpg" alt="Followers of @arsenal, @persie_official and @FlyingEmirates" width="430" height="323" /></a></p>
<p>Might <a href="http://twitter.com/FlyingEmirates">The Emirates Group</a> (official sponsors of Premiership giants <a href="http://twitter.com/arsenal">Arsenal</a>) hope for slightly more overlap with followers of the club and their star striker <a href="http://twitter.com/persie_official">Robin van Persie</a>?</p>
<p>If someone could just hurry up and invent a time machine, we could go back and benchmark and then monitor the affect, if any, this sponsorship deal has had on the appeal of Emirates to their target market.</p>
<p><strong>And now, let&#8217;s throw in a hashtag to spice things up a little&#8230;</strong></p>
<p><a title="Followers of #c4thepromise, @mailonline and @guardian by NixonMcInnes, on Flickr" rel="shadowbox[tweetspot];content=http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5303/5632500656_39f82ffeec_o.png" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nixonmcinnes/5632500656/"><img src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5303/5632500656_444e0c6aae.jpg" alt="Followers of #c4thepromise, @mailonline and @guardian" width="430" height="323" /></a></p>
<p>Some hashtags naturally have finite lifespans, particularly hashtags for events and TV programmes. It’s possible, therefore, to apply this methodology to such hashtags, by capturing the conversation over the duration of the hashtag, and then pulling out the distinct set of contributors to the conversation.</p>
<p>We did just this with our <a href="http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-promise/articles/twitter-tracker">Datacopter</a> instance for Channel 4’s 4-part drama series <a href="http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-promise">The Promise</a> earlier this year, and here’s a snapshot at how that conversation mapped against followers of <a href="http://twitter.com/mailonline">The Daily Mail</a> and <a href="http://twitter.com/guardian">The Guardian</a>. Interesting how the followers of these 2 daily nationals seem to be split in this particular conversation, with there being virtually no overlap between all 3 sets.</p>
<p><strong>Other possible uses</strong></p>
<p>These are some ideas <a href="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk/people/beth"><abbr title="Beth Granter">Beth</abbr></a> had for some other possible uses for analyses of this kind:</p>
<ul>
<li>Competitor analysis</li>
<li>Audience persona profiling</li>
<li>Analysis of potential reach of key messages to specific audiences, e.g. comparison of followers with users of a hashtag relating to a PR crisis</li>
</ul>
<p>As always, we welcome further insight and feedback in the comments below, but also feel free to leave requests for any other comparisons you’d like to see, I&#8217;ll try and cover as many as I can!</p>
<p>Tune in next time when I’ll introduce a technique for comparing similarity between any number of Twitter accounts, using <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cluster_analysis">clustering</a>!</p>
