		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Crowd-sourcing the office stereo, using Twitter and Spotify]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk/2010/01/07/crowd-sourcing-the-office-stereo-using-twitter-and-spotify/" />
		<id>http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk/?p=1728</id>
		<updated>2010-01-22T15:00:34Z</updated>
		<published>2010-01-07T17:52:23Z</published>
		<category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="Development" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="Funny" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="twitter" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="api" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="mashup" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="python" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="spotify" /><category scheme="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk" term="streaming" />		<summary type="html"><![CDATA[Amazingly, it is now possible to play songs directly through our office speakers via the magic of Twitter... details within...]]></summary>
		<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk/2010/01/07/crowd-sourcing-the-office-stereo-using-twitter-and-spotify/"><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/joriel/2415728050/"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-1731" title="Grand Master and his Ghetto Blasters..." src="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/2415728050_c78ee32b67_o-430x430.jpg" alt="Grand Master and his Ghetto Blasters..." width="430" height="430" /></a></p>
<p>While idly experimenting with the newfangled, <em>real-time</em> <a href="http://apiwiki.twitter.com/Streaming-API-Documentation">Twitter Streaming API</a> yesterday, I decided to have a little bit of fun, to try and make life a little more interesting! In the interests of innovation and openness, I thought I would take some time out to share these experiments with you&#8230;</p>
<p><strong>Experiment #1</strong></p>
<p>A little Python script, <a href="http://gist.github.com/270452">tweet_speak.py</a>, that reads tweets aloud (using the OS X <tt>say</tt> command), from either a specified list of followees, or tracked keywords. Could be useful for some form of buzz-monitoring/alert-type system, as <a href="http://twitter.com/willmcinnes/status/7480039425">noted</a> by <a href="http://www.nixonmcinnes.co.uk/people/will">Mr. Willeeumm</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Experiment #2</strong></p>
<p>This is where things get really interesting/silly (*delete as appropriate).</p>
<p>Building on Experiment #1, I setup a dedicated Twitter account for the office stereo, <a href="http://twitter.com/nmstereo">@nmstereo</a>, to which anyone can now <a href="http://twitter.com/steveWINton/status/7481739375">direct a song request</a>, via the form of a <a href="http://www.spotify.com/blog/archives/2008/01/14/linking-to-spotify/">Spotify track URI</a>, which will then be dutifully played on the NixonMcInnes office stereo, e.g.</p>
<p><tt>@nmstereo spotify:track:3Zk68KkPWgvfx8Bs0gqYDw</tt></p>
<p>So, now, EVERYONE can join in the fun of the beloved, weekly Love Hour™ (every Wednesday, 3pm sharp, folks)!</p>
<p>Unfortunately, you won&#8217;t be able to hear the song you request (unless of course you&#8217;re in the office, duh!), but we&#8217;re sure to enjoy your selection and, fear not, we never censor anything on the office stereo!!!</p>
<p>We&#8217;ll see how long we can keep this running for, currently it&#8217;s not going to scale very well, and if we get too many requests for <a href="spotify:track:4psRoaOLrAI1fiDWQHgiZX">It&#8217;s Raining Men</a>, then we may have to take it down, but, until then, let&#8217;s have a little fun, shall we? :)</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UPDATE</strong> (2010-01-08): Here&#8217;s the Python script, <a href="http://gist.github.com/271686">tweetify.py</a>, that we&#8217;re using to hook our stereo up to Twitter!</p>
<p><strong>UPDATE</strong> (2010-01-14): The Twitter/Spotify revolution continues with this @nmstereo clone, <a href="http://twitter.com/tweepify">@tweepify</a>!</p>
<p><strong>UPDATE</strong> (2010-01-20): Here&#8217;s a less spammy Web interface for requesting songs on @nmstereo (oh, and you can listen along, too!): <a href="http://nmstereo.appspot.com/">nmstereo.appspot.com</a></p>
<p><strong>UPDATE</strong> (2010-01-22): Another implementation spotted in the wild: <a href="https://twitter.com/nlgit">@nlgit</a>. w00T!</p>
